What is a CDN? ğŸŒğŸš€
CDN stands for Content Delivery Network. It is a globally distributed network of servers that deliver web content (HTML, CSS, JavaScript, images, videos, etc.) to users faster and more efficiently based on their geographical location.

Why Do We Use a CDN? ğŸ¤”
âœ… Faster Website Loading â€“ Content is served from the nearest server instead of a single central server.
âœ… Reduced Server Load â€“ Distributes traffic across multiple servers, preventing overload.
âœ… Improved Reliability & Uptime â€“ If one server fails, another takes over.
âœ… Better Security â€“ Protects against DDoS attacks and other cyber threats.
âœ… Lower Bandwidth Costs â€“ Reduces the amount of data transferred from the main server.
âœ… Improved SEO â€“ Faster websites improve Google rankings.

How Does a CDN Work? ğŸ”„
1ï¸âƒ£ User requests a web page.
2ï¸âƒ£ The CDN finds the nearest server with cached content.
3ï¸âƒ£ The nearest CDN server delivers the requested content quickly.

Example of Using a CDN in React
Instead of downloading React manually, you can use a CDN to load it:

html
Copy
Edit
<script src="https://unpkg.com/react@18/umd/react.development.js" crossorigin="anonymous"></script>
<script src="https://unpkg.com/react-dom@18/umd/react-dom.development.js" crossorigin="anonymous"></script>
âœ… No need to install React via NPM
âœ… Faster loading due to global distribution

Popular CDN Providers
1ï¸âƒ£ Cloudflare CDN ğŸŒ
2ï¸âƒ£ Akamai CDN
3ï¸âƒ£ Amazon CloudFront (AWS)
4ï¸âƒ£ Google Cloud CDN
5ï¸âƒ£ Microsoft Azure CDN
6ï¸âƒ£ UNPKG & jsDelivr (for serving NPM packages like React)

When Should You Use a CDN?
âœ” Hosting static files (CSS, JS, images, fonts).
âœ” Serving large-scale applications with users worldwide.
âœ” Reducing server load for high-traffic websites.

